		<div class="post" id="post-1731639">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1731639)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1731639">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djoric" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(388108); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=388108&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227596" alt="Djoric" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=388108)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djoric" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(388108); return false;" >Djoric</a></span> <span class="odate time_1363368083 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Mar 2013 17:21</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1731639">
									

<p>Allow me to offer a justification.</p>
<p>The Foundation, being the organization whose viewpoint the site follows, is obsessed with putting things in boxes. It is the small child that refuses to let his meat and mashed potatoes touch, and don't you even <em>think</em> about putting gravy on it. This, I feel, can be damaging to the overall universe: Somehow, the perspective of the in-universe Foundation reached the out-of-universe Foundation, leading to such silly things as the old &quot;there is no canon&quot; mantra and the knee-jerk reaction to any sort of cross-testing, things we thankfully are moving away from.</p>
<p>But this is outside the Foundation's jurisdiction. I can mix my meat and potatoes here and put as much gravy on as I want. Every single thing referenced here had some reason to be there: it was either uncontained, or had the possibility of being uncontained.</p>
<p>Let's look at who we have: GRU-P agents, MCF workers, some Serpent's Hand, some AWCY, and some in-fill of unaligned people. Then we have a band from Syncope, a guy from 1329, Mr. Lost, the commie spiders, a robot from Funland, Builder Bear, Sami and Dan, the time-traveling wife, and Bigfoot. This is a pretty reasonable group to see in an anomalous bar. None of them break suspension of disbelief by being there. If I had gone all 682 AND 173 AND 076 AND CLEF R ALL HAVIN DRINKS, that would be patently ridiculous.</p>
<p>So, I'm somewhat curious: how would you go about writing a bar with a generally anomalous clientele? I <em>could</em> make up new things to fit in, but the plain fact of the matter is that the Foundation universe already has plenty of things to work with, and I would much rather have a universe that feels like a universe, rather than a bunch of unconnected bits and bobs that have no gravy.</p>

							</div>

								
					
